Ed,<br><br>
Thanks for your response. The volunteers have borne more of the brunt of service and responsibility for the war than the draftees. No disrespect meant, but a common response to an angry volunteer could be, &quot;What the hell you complaining about? You volunteered.&quot;<br><br>
I have a great amount of respect for you and your service, Ed. You do me a great honor by engaging in dialogue with me, a reluctant draftee.<br><br>
As for asking &quot;why&quot; before going to war, our parents didn't have to ask that question on Dec 7, 1941, did they? They knew. You make a great point in your last post of this thread when you alluded to the &quot;what ifs&quot; about a united America making a difference. Contrast the Gulf of Tonkin (not in hindsight, though) with Pearl Harbor.<br><br>
Best to you and yours, Ed.<br><br>
Cook,<br><br>
I had the good fortune to have a mom and dad who instilled in me an abiding respect for all people. <br><br>
I could not question your motivation for serving in Vietnam. Again, as I have said, I respect you and I respect your service. If it means anything to you, I thank you.<br><br>
We just don't look at things the same way. <br><br>
My love for the Vietnamese people wasn't contingent on politics, or saving them from communism. The lessons I learned from them are the most valuable lessons a young person can learn. They persevered.<br><br>
Your ideals are those that should be everyone's ideals. We should be willing to lay our lives on the line for freedom for other people. Wasn't it Jesus who said ( I'm paraphrasing) that the greatest thing another person could do was to give his life for another?<br><br>
That is not what I always saw in Vietnam. That is not how America's people were always represented. <br><br>
We all saw it. The mama sans who worked in the rear area, picking through the garbage behind the mess hall. Why did Vietnamese kids have to eat out of the garbage?
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


